Data Visualization

Distribution of the scores according to the quiz takerâ€™s age

As seen in the visualization, the young adult and adult groups are very close in terms of their score, there are 2 age groups that stands out, which are children (<18) and older adults (>55). Children group has the lowest score in all four groups, which is expected. Older adults have the highest score of all four groups. Which is not much surprising since the virus is particularly dangerous for older people, but this is not much accountable, since there are only 2 samples from the older adult age group.

Distribution of the Total.scores

From the graph it can be clearly seen that the scores distribution follows the normal distribution. Most people get a score of 60 or 70, which is a mediocre level of knowledge about the virus and effects.

Distribution of scores according to the quiz takerâ€™s education level

Unsurprisingly, we can see the samples with the lowest education level, which is â€˜primary schoolâ€™ doesnâ€™t have as much success in the test as the people with higher education, But there seems to be not much difference between the â€˜Highscoolâ€™ and â€˜Universityâ€™ education levels, other than the variation.

Distribution of the scores with respect to the smoker/non-smoker property

Interestingly, people who smoke has clearly more success at the test, It can be associated with some of the questions, we can further investigate the reason.

Testing mean scores based on gender

Ha: data is not normally distributed

Testing a Hyphotesis

Letâ€™s create a null hypothesis,
Ho: mean scores of both male and female are the same muFemale = muMale
An alternative hypothesis,
Ha: mean scores of males and females are not the same. muFemale != muMale

## 
##  Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  Total.scores[Cinsiyet == "Erkek"] and Total.scores[Cinsiyet == "KadÄ±n"]

## mean of x mean of y

confidence interval includes mu=0. [-14.92231, 12.15760]
t(o) (0.20726) < t(t) ~2
Fail to reject Null
There is no evidence that the true mean values for males and females is different.

Testing the answer to a specific question as smoker/non smoker

In the visualizations, an interesting result caught my attention; The smokers tend to have clearly better scores than non-smokers. This might be associated with the question; â€˜KoronavirÃ¼sten en ciddi etkilenen gruplar hangileridir?â€™, which smoking is an answer option.

Since every question is worth of 10 points, i thought i could test an alternative hyphotesis: â€˜The mean difference of Total.scores between smokers and non smokers is greater than 10â€™

Testing a Hyphotesis

Letâ€™s look at a plot to see the answers for that particular question (â€˜KoronavirÃ¼sten en ciddi etkilenen gruplar hangileridir?â€™) described by the question; (â€˜Sigara kullanÄ±yor musunuz?â€™)
